<div id="review_467121728" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/467121728" />
    <a title="Francisco" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2986010-francisco"><img alt="Francisco" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442487409p2/2986010.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/467121728?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Francisco" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Francisco" href="/user/show/2986010-francisco">Francisco</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400032662" href="/book/show/846564.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer467121728" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10638043746246308072">Mourid Barghouti, now an established poet, returns to his hometown in Israeli-occupied Palestine after thirty years of exile. Here are some of the things I learned from this book: That loss is not abstract, it is concrete. The fig tree in the courtyard that is no longer there. The olive oil to dip your morning bread that now comes from a store. The school house wall plastered with political slogans. The dead brother. The friend that no longer speaks to you. The lost love. These absences are real</span>
  <span id="freeText10638043746246308072" style="display:none">Mourid Barghouti, now an established poet, returns to his hometown in Israeli-occupied Palestine after thirty years of exile. Here are some of the things I learned from this book: That loss is not abstract, it is concrete. The fig tree in the courtyard that is no longer there. The olive oil to dip your morning bread that now comes from a store. The school house wall plastered with political slogans. The dead brother. The friend that no longer speaks to you. The lost love. These absences are real. You can touch them. They live and go on living in so many places, so many things. It amazes me how a book like this, so personal, so full of poetry, so without hatred or even anger, can be so powerful. There's no political agenda here. Berghouti simply describes displacement concretely. He makes you feel homeless there, in Ramallah, and in your own life. That's the book's power. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10638043746246308072" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


