<div id="review_3086815873" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3086815873" />
    <a title="Sleepless Dreamer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7614560-sleepless-dreamer"><img alt="Sleepless Dreamer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1431177042p2/7614560.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3086815873?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sleepless Dreamer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sleepless Dreamer" href="/user/show/7614560-sleepless-dreamer">Sleepless Dreamer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400032662" href="/book/show/846564.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7614560-sleepless-dreamer?shelf=reading-a-book-from-every-country">reading-a-book-from-every-country</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3086815873" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16959983402062752139">The other day, a friend from class asked me what I&apos;m reading. Knowing that she&apos;s very right wing, I told her about this book and said that I will read every perspective about the conflict. We had a nice conversation about pluralism and such. She was claiming that pluralism leads to a loss of your own narrative while I very much want to believe that a person can contain an understanding of complex and contrasting views. <br/><br/>Anyway, this book tells us about his return to his childhood home thirty year</span>
  <span id="freeText16959983402062752139" style="display:none">The other day, a friend from class asked me what I'm reading. Knowing that she's very right wing, I told her about this book and said that I will read every perspective about the conflict. We had a nice conversation about pluralism and such. She was claiming that pluralism leads to a loss of your own narrative while I very much want to believe that a person can contain an understanding of complex and contrasting views. <br /><br />Anyway, this book tells us about his return to his childhood home thirty years later. I find the conversation about the right of return fascinating. Of course, I also find the fact that descendants of Palestinians are also considered refugees also absolutely interesting. <br /><br />I've always gotten the impression that these Palestinian descendants don't want to actually live here. They want to know their homeland exists the way they dream of it and they want the ability to visit but truly, I wonder how many Palestinians descendants would actually abandon their lives in the states, in Hungary, in Denmark in order to live here? It's even more intriguing when you consider the refugee camps in Jordan and how the Jordanian population depends on Palestinians at this point. <br /><br />This book brings it up a little bit. One character urges Palestinians to come and as a Jew, I couldn't help but think of how ingrained Israel is in our prayers, our religion is a peoplehood, it's a nation and it's so very connected to this territory in a way that perhaps younger generations of Palestinians can relate to through the education that they receive from their (grand) parents who were refugees. <br /><br />In any case, I had hoped to get this insight into the world of someone that left his home to study abroad and abruptly learned that in this time, there was a war and his home as he knew it is gone. That's scary. Most of my dorm floor is international students and I can't imagine how broken they would be if something happened to their home. <br /><br />This is not what this book was. Barghouti (that family is so wild, it feels weird to use his last name) writes with this dreamy style. I often struggled to figure out exactly what he's talking about, if it's the sixties or the nineties. It was very frustrating. I think the translation was also problematic and hey, inshallah in a few years I'll be able to read it in Arabic. <br /><br />Beyond this, the book doesn't have a very collected narrative. It jumps around in such a way that makes it challenging to paint a perspective. I realize that this is written by a poet but come on, this is biographical, you can do better. <br /><br />When it came down to the content, I was fascinated though! As an Israeli living now in 2019, I view things differently. Everyone acknowledges Oslo was a mistake (fun fact, I was embarrassingly old before I realized that Oslo is actually a city and not just a political thing that we all complain about). We grew up celebrating the six day war, seeing it as a victory. We think about the disengagement and the rockets from Gaza and the deaths from the Intifada. <br /><br />There's a part here where he talks about martyrs getting paid by the Palestinian Authority. I've always read this as "The PA pays terrorists". I still read it this way but I think this was the first time I ever stopped and felt like I could see how hard it must be to be a wife of someone that sacrificed themselves for independence (and ahh, every time I walk down the street of my home, I cross next to a bus station where a bus exploded with such a martyr and killed a few people but when you look at the number, more Palestinians died in the intifadas but they were the ones who initiated them and nothing is ever simple or painless here). <br /><br />Of course, Barghouti jumps over the more uncomfortable sides of the story. He doesn't say who started the six day war, what happened in 1948, how Israel has been constantly outnumbered and surrounded, what happened in the intifadas. And in the same vein, he talks a few times about Sabra and Shatila massacres which we learned about in school in passing and not enough. <br /><br />When I was in Taiwan, a statement I heard over and over was, "yes, we want independence but no, I'm not willing to die for that". Of course, this came from the 7ish people I spoke to but still, it was such a difference from the narrative here where everyone is willing to die to get to the political state they want. <br /><br />Barghouti spends a remarkable amount of time observing soldiers and pondering what they're thinking. He seems to want to bring up the Israeli view in order to disagree with it and yet, he absolutely fails at understanding what Israelis feel. <br /><br />This is highlighted in the last chapter when he talks about Rabin's speech. I get it, Barghouti desperately wants to paint Israelis as land hungry villains who thrive on occupying Palestinians and sending their youth to die on battle grounds. It's harder to understand that the occupation was essentially a mistake, a moment of legal confusion. That soldiers are 18 year olds and yes, we've got to acknowledge each other's pain. That Barghouti can speak the truth and Rabin can also speak the truth and neither one of them is misleading. <br /><br />And I think about my friend and how angry she'd be about how Barghouti can see the pain of martyrs and not the pain of soldiers. How frustrated she'd be by how he ignores that this land is (also) ours. <br /><br />The other day I found myself thinking that if I'll ever actually work in politics, my very rambling reviews might show up and haunt me. I hope to grow so much in the next 2.5 years (and maybe more) of studying politics and understand more. <br /><br />Right now, what stands out is how Israelis who talk about peace don't want to talk about being victims while Palestinians who want to talk about peace don't want to talk about violence on their side. Israelis that don't believe in peace refuse to acknowledge Palestinian pain or sympathize with their story. <br /><br />And all of this is a problem because I don't think Palestinians understand that I grew up learning that a woman with a hijab and a big coat can explode in a bus and therefore, if I see one, I should be aware of my surroundings. Is this racism? Absolutely. And yet, this is also something that happened again and again. It is not just racism, it is fear that was learned. It can be unlearned but only if it's addressed in its complexity, not just as racism and not just as a valid concern. <br /><br />And the army is oppressing and inherently violent but I remember what it felt like to drink coffee surrounded by friends on base and how every soldier I saw was an instant friend just because we were both wearing an army uniform. It's never one or the other. <br /><br />There is so so much that I do not understand about Palestinian experiences. We're never going to understand each other if we don't speak earnestly. I'm not interested in conversations that aren't honest anymore which is leading me to be frustrated with every peace meeting ever. <br /><br />I could write more, there's so much to write. This book opened doors about this conflict that I didn't entirely think of before. I want to open all of those doors. Do I recommend this book? Well, if you are prepared for more poetry than politics, sure. <br /><br /><b> what I'm taking with me </b><br />• I understood that he left his home to study in Egypt when 1967 happened, I hope this is true. <br />• I wonder where's the bridge. <br />• guys, I've been putting a ton of time in my Arabic and like I'm slowly feeling an improvement!! <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16959983402062752139" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


