<div id="review_3832148792" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3832148792" />
    <a title="Molly Kent" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18015562-molly-kent"><img alt="Molly Kent" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616338652p2/18015562.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3832148792?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Molly Kent" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Molly Kent" href="/user/show/18015562-molly-kent">Molly Kent</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400032662" href="/book/show/846564.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3832148792" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1975409268152153191">In the version of this I read, with an introduction by Edward Said, Said writes that people &quot;haunt&quot; the pages. <br/><br/>He&apos;s right. The dead of this novel* curl themselves around every page. Their spirits slide between your fingers and dance in the shadows as you read. The spirits of the dead in this book can&apos;t rest, because there&apos;s nowhere for them to rest. Haunt is exactly the right word because I feel haunted. <br/><br/>It&apos;s easy for anybody, as a human, to feel like they don&apos;t belong. But most of us can answer</span>
  <span id="freeText1975409268152153191" style="display:none">In the version of this I read, with an introduction by Edward Said, Said writes that people "haunt" the pages. <br /><br />He's right. The dead of this novel* curl themselves around every page. Their spirits slide between your fingers and dance in the shadows as you read. The spirits of the dead in this book can't rest, because there's nowhere for them to rest. Haunt is exactly the right word because I feel haunted. <br /><br />It's easy for anybody, as a human, to feel like they don't belong. But most of us can answer the question of where we come from easily, without hesitation or anxiety. That, I think, is what is haunting me the most. The idea that some people truly cannot say they belong anywhere. Can you imagine? <br /><br />*This is not a novel. Calling it a novel does it a disservice. It's poetry. Every word intentional. It's beautiful. Writer and translator were perfect. <br /><br />P.S. This review is pretentious but I don't know how else to write it without just putting a link to a GIF of someone crying in a hole. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1975409268152153191" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


