<div id="review_3452567481" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3452567481" />
    <a title="Abidha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56207068-abidha"><img alt="Abidha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1522015952p2/56207068.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3452567481?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abidha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abidha" href="/user/show/56207068-abidha">Abidha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400032662" href="/book/show/846564.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3452567481" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1383208286732898832">I didn’t know what to expect from this apart from having an inkling that Barghouti was a huge figure in the Arab literature world, having read this I understand why. <br/><br/>The book beautifully touches on Baghouti’s experience of living in exile and returning to his homeland after thirty years. The pain of separation and excitement of his homecoming that Barghouti writes about, is one that I’ve never felt but only heard of from my Kashmiri friends. <br/><br/>Personally, for the longest of time, I have romanticis</span>
  <span id="freeText1383208286732898832" style="display:none">I didn’t know what to expect from this apart from having an inkling that Barghouti was a huge figure in the Arab literature world, having read this I understand why. <br /><br />The book beautifully touches on Baghouti’s experience of living in exile and returning to his homeland after thirty years. The pain of separation and excitement of his homecoming that Barghouti writes about, is one that I’ve never felt but only heard of from my Kashmiri friends. <br /><br />Personally, for the longest of time, I have romanticised the idea of city-hopping &amp; working but reading about Barghouti’s experience of exile living in Amman, Budapest, Beirut &amp; Cairo, made me appreciate the beauty and blessing there is in having a place that is permanent, a place that you can call home and one that will always welcome you back. <br /><br />As the book is translated, I’m sure like all translated work it does not do full justice to its original work, however despite this, there are some quotes in this book that will just hit you, like the quote below; <br /><br />“....we did not lose Palestine to a debate, we lost it to force. When we were Palestine, we were not afraid of Jewish people, we did not hate them, we did not make an enemy of them. Europe of the Middle she’s hated them, but not us. Ferdinand and Isabella hated them but not us. Hitler hated them but not us. But when they took our entire space and exiled us from it they put both us and themselves outside the law of equality”. <br /><br />Inna Lillahi wa inna ilaihi raji'un. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1383208286732898832" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


