  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3996757395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3996757395" />
    <a title="Bagus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32952691-bagus"><img alt="Bagus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627022630p2/32952691.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3996757395?book_show_action=true">Oct 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bagus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bagus" href="/user/show/32952691-bagus">Bagus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780747574705" href="/book/show/430641.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32952691-bagus?shelf=2021-read">2021-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32952691-bagus?shelf=migration-diversity">migration-diversity</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32952691-bagus?shelf=books-i-own">books-i-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32952691-bagus?shelf=middle-east">middle-east</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32952691-bagus?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3996757395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6726775702129503218"><i>I Saw Ramallah</i> opens with a scene of the Mourid Barghouti’s return to his homeland after thirty years of exile, with him crossing the bridge across the Jordan River which connects Amman and Ramallah. He was 22 when the Six-Day War happened in 1967, after which he was barred from entering Palestine along with countless displaced Palestinians who were forced to live in exile in the years that followed. The Palestinian land is so close through their eyes, yet so far away as the Occupation hindered </span>
  <span id="freeText6726775702129503218" style="display:none"><i>I Saw Ramallah</i> opens with a scene of the Mourid Barghouti’s return to his homeland after thirty years of exile, with him crossing the bridge across the Jordan River which connects Amman and Ramallah. He was 22 when the Six-Day War happened in 1967, after which he was barred from entering Palestine along with countless displaced Palestinians who were forced to live in exile in the years that followed. The Palestinian land is so close through their eyes, yet so far away as the Occupation hindered the possibilities of them entering the homeland. Mourid Barghouti speaks from his soul in giving the voice to Palestinian diaspora abroad who yearned to see their homeland again, who died in bizarre circumstances while living in exile without ever seeing their land again, who were forced to live with scattered family members only to be connected through phone lines. <br /><br />As <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/16770310.Edward_W__Said" title="Edward W. Said" rel="nofollow noopener">Edward W. Said</a> says in his foreword to this book, the political circumstances described by the author in this book is hardly abstract or ideologically driven. The critical opinions of Mourid Barghouti in this book towards the life experienced by Palestinians both at their homeland under Israeli Occupation and in exile abroad are narrated through the circumstances in real experience. The way the author describes his experience is lyrical, true to his main occupation as a poet, and the way <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51563.Ahdaf_Soueif" title="Ahdaf Soueif" rel="nofollow noopener">Ahdaf Soueif</a> brings this element into the English translation is something to be commended as well. At times, the author could be intense in describing the loss of loved ones. Sometimes funny anecdotes could fill up the stories too such as when his family members gathered for an occasion in Geneva, with the authorities checking their passports feeling confused since they all had the same surname—al-Barghouti—but the passports are from Jordan, Syria, the United States, Algeria, Britain, and some other countries, such were the circumstances of exile life.<br /><br />It’s not wrong of Edward Said to say Mourid Barghouti’s experience as a fine existential account of Palestinian displacement, of the pain of continually living in the state of limbo, of having nowhere to return to. Seeing Ramallah for the first time after thirty years gave the author a sense of disorientation with mostly familiar scenes, yet some people had died or simply moved somewhere else around the globe, or places that no longer looked the same with the time that passed. Barghouti asks, “How did I sing for my homeland when I did not know it?” In the end, he argues that the Occupation stops Palestine from progress, with places that seem underdeveloped and displaced people, turning the country itself into a mere symbol.<br /><br />Barghouti’s exile did not stop with his displacement from Palestine to Egypt where he obtained her degree and married his wife Radwa Ashour in 1970. The couples had just had their son, Tamim, in 1977 when Barghouti was deported by the Egyptian government of Anwar al-Sadat as at that time Egypt was engaged in peace talks with Israel that led to the signing of Camp David Accords in 1979. As part of this cooperation, the Anwar al-Sadat’s regime banished many prominent Palestinians from Egypt, sometimes even targeting someone with no political affiliations such as Barghouti himself. For a long period, Barghouti was forced to live in Budapest between the 1970s and the 1980s with frequent visits from his wife and son from Egypt to there. <br /><br />This book is too emotional for people who seek facts, although there is factual information as well that Barghouti includes here and there. The timeline does not follow anachronistic order, as Barghouti has this tendency to bring flashbacks frequently while recounting his story, so expect to do a bit of thinking into when in the timeline Barghouti’s flashbacks would fit. Nevertheless, I’d totally recommend this book for anyone looking to understand and get better perspectives about Palestinian lives and Palestinian-in-exiles.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6726775702129503218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

