<div id="review_1162187421" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1162187421" />
    <a title="Reem" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9455757-reem"><img alt="Reem" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427314317p2/9455757.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1162187421?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Reem" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Reem" href="/user/show/9455757-reem">Reem</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/7673347">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1162187421" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer898077785930785469">I often think of books as gifts, and this novel is the most precious one of all. I am grateful to Mourid Barghouti who has allowed me to see my Palestine in a whole different light, my parents and grandparents&apos; Palestine, the one we read about in history books but never had the opportunity to experience because by the time we&apos;d grown up walls surrounded us and the colors in the country had been muted. <br/>In one passage, Barghouti describes how the world knows Jerusalem only as the &quot;Holy City&quot; and t</span>
  <span id="freeText898077785930785469" style="display:none">I often think of books as gifts, and this novel is the most precious one of all. I am grateful to Mourid Barghouti who has allowed me to see my Palestine in a whole different light, my parents and grandparents' Palestine, the one we read about in history books but never had the opportunity to experience because by the time we'd grown up walls surrounded us and the colors in the country had been muted. <br />In one passage, Barghouti describes how the world knows Jerusalem only as the "Holy City" and the center of conflict, and no one knows what lies in its alleyways and how the people of the city laugh and love and grieve, much like anyone else. This is what reading this book felt like: a Palestinian story encompassing the ups and downs and the silly way we Palestinians make jokes about our situation just to get through it. This novel is like an inside look at a small fragment of a Palestinian life (or an intertwined web of several lives) and being able to witness it through Barghouti's words is an absolute privilege and pleasure.</span>
  <a data-text-id="898077785930785469" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


