  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3121468457" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3121468457" />
    <a title="gulru" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6075612-gulru"><img alt="gulru" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606028267p2/6075612.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3121468457?book_show_action=true">Oct 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="gulru" class="user" itemprop="url" name="gulru" href="/user/show/6075612-gulru">gulru</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400032662" href="/book/show/846564.I_Saw_Ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6075612-gulru?shelf=favs">favs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6075612-gulru?shelf=nf-biography">nf-biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3121468457" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10905279192377834878">You haven&apos;t felt and understood displacement until you&apos;ve read this. This is one of the most beautiful and most personally impactful books I&apos;ve read in recent memory. It&apos;s solemn yet also heartwarming. Informative yet personal. It&apos;s hard to describe the feelings it evokes; I&apos;m mostly just overwhelmed. <br/><br/>I particularly appreciated how he could tie vague descriptions of political events into the real and monumental way they affected the lives of everyone around him and even himself as a person. I th</span>
  <span id="freeText10905279192377834878" style="display:none">You haven't felt and understood displacement until you've read this. This is one of the most beautiful and most personally impactful books I've read in recent memory. It's solemn yet also heartwarming. Informative yet personal. It's hard to describe the feelings it evokes; I'm mostly just overwhelmed. <br /><br />I particularly appreciated how he could tie vague descriptions of political events into the real and monumental way they affected the lives of everyone around him and even himself as a person. I think I had become desensitised to seeing tragedy on the news. That's impossible to say after reading this. <br /><br />I do wish I could read this in Arabic. I could tell I was missing out on the pieces lost in the colonizer's tongue. <br /><br />Despite that, I'm about to post a monster of a list of my favourite quotes. This isn't even a complete list; many of my absolute favourite lines needed the whole page with them to properly convey their meaning. So this is just an abridged list for my personal collection. <br /><br />----------------------- FAVOURITE QUOTES <br />-  The stranger is the person who renews his Residence Permit. <br />- I asked myself, what is so special about it except that we have lost it? It is a land, like any land. We sing for it only so that we may remember the humiliation of having had it taken from us.<br />-  Politics is the family at breakfast. Who is there and who is absent and why. <br />-  As for Jerusalem I was not allowed to enter it or see it. Even the road to Ramallah that used to go by Jerusalem they changed via a complex of winding roads so that we may not see the city even from the car window. <br />- They send us one message, all the time and in every way: 'We are the masters here.'<br />- The Jerusalem of houseplants, cobbled alleys and narrow walkways. The Jerusalem of clothes-lines. This is the city of our senses, our bodies and our childhood. The Jerusalem that we walk in without much noticing its 'sacredness,' because we are in it, because it is us. The world is concerned with the 'status' of Jerusalem, the ideas and the myth of Jerusalem, but our lives in Jerusalem and the Jerusalem of our lives do not concern it. [...] Now, I cannot see either Jerusalem of the ideas or Jerusalem of the clothes-lines. Israel, with the excuse of the ideas, has occupied the land. <br />-  We cannot live there or leave there, we cannot get bored with Jerusalem and leave it for Nablus or Damascus or Cairo or America. We cannot grumble about it as people grumble about their tiresome capitals. Perhaps the worst thing about occupied cities is that their children cannot make fun of them.<br />-  The Occupation kept the Palestinian village static and turned our cities back into villages. We do not want to regain the past but to regain the future. <br />-  I was never particularly interested in the theoretical discussions around who has the right to Palestine, because we did not lose Palestine in a debate, we lost it to force. When we were Palestine, we were not afraid of the Jews. We did not hate them, we did not make an enemy of them. Europe of the Middle Ages hated them, not us. But when they took our entire space and exiled us from it they pushed us and themselves outside the law of equality. They took the space with the power of the sacred and with the sacredness of power. <br />-  Our dead are scattered at every land. Sometimes we did not know where to go with their corpses; the capitals of the world refused to receive as corpses as they were refused to receive us alive. And if the dead by displacement and the dead by weapons and the dead by longing and dead by simple death are martyrs, and if poems are true and each martyr is a rose, we can claim to have made a garden of the world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10905279192377834878" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

