<div id="review_4092345022" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4092345022" />
    <a title="Anjum Haz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/80850132-anjum-haz"><img alt="Anjum Haz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626797586p2/80850132.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4092345022?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anjum Haz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anjum Haz" href="/user/show/80850132-anjum-haz">Anjum Haz</a>
      </span>

          marked it as unfinished


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19785922-i-saw-ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/80850132-anjum-haz?shelf=memoir">memoir</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/80850132-anjum-haz?shelf=middle-east">middle-east</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4092345022" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17892094287246357673">I was looking for a book to know the land of Palestine, get familiar with their people and the burning issues of their land. After a small research on internet, I picked up this memoir by a Palestinian poet. <br/><br/>The book started with the author crossing a bridge. A bridge that connected his people with the other side of the world or disconnected, for that matter. While crossing the bridge, flashbacks came to the author. Flashback of his relatives and friends and people whose identities the author di</span>
  <span id="freeText17892094287246357673" style="display:none">I was looking for a book to know the land of Palestine, get familiar with their people and the burning issues of their land. After a small research on internet, I picked up this memoir by a Palestinian poet. <br /><br />The book started with the author crossing a bridge. A bridge that connected his people with the other side of the world or disconnected, for that matter. While crossing the bridge, flashbacks came to the author. Flashback of his relatives and friends and people whose identities the author didn't care to reveal. <br /><br />As the memoir goes on, I feel that I can't picture Ramallah. How modern is the place? Is it like Europe or Turkey or India? Does it snow there? How are the people? Do the women wear scarves there? It was like only Mourid Barghouti saw Ramallah and not the readers. <br /><br />I felt that the author is just expressing an emotional account of suffering with his poetic writing. But I was expecting more than this. I wanted to read a book to see Palestine in my eyes, as much or less as possible. And this book would be a touchy one for a Palestinian reader maybe who knows all the streets by their names and who has no difficulty picturing and understanding the land. But it’s not for me, not now. So, I quit reading after going through about one-third of the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17892094287246357673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


