<div id="review_167110029" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/167110029" />
    <a title="Andy Perdue" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5157001-andy-perdue"><img alt="Andy Perdue" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1353476476p2/5157001.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/167110029?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andy Perdue" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andy Perdue" href="/user/show/5157001-andy-perdue">Andy Perdue</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780307486141" href="/book/show/6988251-i-saw-ramallah">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5157001-andy-perdue?shelf=mideast">mideast</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer167110029" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2562851593708149972">Mourid Barghouti&apos;s &quot;I Saw Ramallah&quot; is a remarkable book. The displaced Palestinian relates his return to Ramallah and Deir Ghassana in the mid-1990s, 30 years after the Six Day War. While one might expect Barghouti to rejoice in his return to the city he hadn&apos;t seen in three decades, in fact it was a mournful experience because of what he&apos;d lost, what he&apos;d missed through those years. In fact, the phrase, &quot;You can&apos;t go home again,&quot; perhaps has never been more aptly applied than by Barghouti in &quot;</span>
  <span id="freeText2562851593708149972" style="display:none">Mourid Barghouti's "I Saw Ramallah" is a remarkable book. The displaced Palestinian relates his return to Ramallah and Deir Ghassana in the mid-1990s, 30 years after the Six Day War. While one might expect Barghouti to rejoice in his return to the city he hadn't seen in three decades, in fact it was a mournful experience because of what he'd lost, what he'd missed through those years. In fact, the phrase, "You can't go home again," perhaps has never been more aptly applied than by Barghouti in "I Saw Ramallah."<br /><br />I have crossed the Allenby Bridge on a few occasions but never gave it much thought. Barghouti's experience was enlightening because of what the bridge between the West Bank and Jordan represents.<br /><br />This is an important book to read in light of everything that has happened in the Middle East over the past century. It is a perspective many of us do not understand. It is beautifully written and translated and should be considered a vital book to read if one hopes to gain a greater picture of the news we read almost daily.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2562851593708149972" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


